(373,7,'2010-05-18 17:53:14','2010-05-18 15:53:14','RSFF was keynote at the WINVR2010 conference held at Iowa State University in Ames, Iowa. Robert E. Wendrich presented the RSFF: Hybrid Design Tool and explained the fundamentals of Raw Shaping design with real tangible materials, haptic tools and assisted by a Virtual Design Assistant.\n\nThe three day [3] conference brought together over 150 participants from all over the globe, speaking about Virtual Reality it\'s application, technologies and design tools. The c6 VR Cave (largest of its kind in the world!) was incredible and exciting, to immerse yourself in virtual worlds this is definitely the kind of tool you would need.\n\n<img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/12052010190.jpg\" /><img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/12052010203.jpg\" /><img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/12052010206.jpg\" /><img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/12052010208.jpg\" /><img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/13052010243.jpg\" />\n\n<a href=\"http://www.Socialrepublick.com\">http://www.Socialrepublick.com</a>','ASME WINVR2010 - ISU Ames, Iowa','','publish','open','open','','winvr2010-isu-ames-iowa','','','2010-05-18 17:53:14','2010-05-18 15:53:14','',0,'http://www.rawshaping.com/?p=373',0,'post','',0),
(407,7,'2010-06-23 11:29:38','2010-06-23 09:29:38','<a title=\"VR-News\" href=\"http://www.vr-news.com/\">http://www.vr-news.com/</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.jvrc2010.org/\">http://www.jvrc2010.org/</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.eurovr-association.org/\">http://www.eurovr-association.org/</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://bridgesmathart.org/\">http://bridgesmathart.org/</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://video.nytimes.com/video/2010/06/23/world/africa/1247468111454/\">http://video.nytimes.com/video/2010/06/23/world/africa/1247468111454/</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://magiclopedia.com/books/bridging-the-two-worlds-the-organizational-dilemma.html\">http://magiclopedia.com/books/bridging-the-two-worlds-the-organizational-dilemma.html </a>\n\n<a href=\"http://petertenklooster.blogspot.com/2010_08_01_archive.html\"></a><a href=\"http://www.bright.nl/station-sassenheim-een-bloembol\"> </a>','Raw Links','','publish','open','open','','raw-links','','','2010-06-23 11:29:38','2010-06-23 09:29:38','',0,'http://www.rawshaping.com/?p=407',0,'post','',0),
(413,7,'2010-06-24 14:34:33','2010-06-24 12:34:33','Raw Shaping Form Finding [RSFF] in Industrial Design Engineering education at the University of Twente in the Netherlands. Second year Bachelor students follow this course in \'finding form through intuitive raw shaping\'. The hybrid design tools [RSFF &amp; LFDS] we have developed during our [re]search, trials and explorations to bridge the gap between physical and virtual design creation processing are partly based on the findings and results derived from experimentations and assignments in conjunction with participating of students. RSFF just recently [2008] became part of the curriculum of IDE on the Education Sub-post (double-click on Education) you will find some interesting outcome of student design interaction.\n\nThe hugely untapped potential of igniting raw ideas, fuzzy notions and unpredictability in shape and form triggered by stimulating intuitive physical interaction based on loosely-fitted organizational techniques has lead us to RSFF.  To create and evoke design content through distributed cognition and randomly creative tinkering in combination with tangible materials and making of physical prototypes [product, service, system or other artifact] while simultaneously making use of real world and virtual reality tools enhances the design creation processing effectively.  With the RSFF approach we support the development of curiosity,  skill, talent, creativity and serendipity by immersing students in cognitive stimulation during design processing that simultaneously enhances their perception and abstract representation. The creation and embedding of aesthetic qualities, imagination, awareness and engagement within design education is pivotal to understand your role as a designer not only as part of the product creation process, but more importantly as part of your vision, responsibility and purpose as a designer towards the often transient Design Industry. Understanding, adding perspective and being knowledgeable on the enduring globalization and manufacturing of consent on topics like sustainability,  eco-efficiency (C2C) and bioenvironmental issues are integrate part and fundamental to design education.\n\nSketching, doodling, drawing, sculpting, modeling and tinkering with two-hands making things will bring out a variety in possible solutions and a richness and diversity in ideas and abstractions. RSFF is about taking your time to think-on-your-feet, evolve your physical actions and colligate your creative sparks leading to improvisation and innovation on-the-fly. Bestowing meaning and passing of judgement are often misleading and disruptive in design processing, RSFF stimulates choice-options and advocates reprieve of opinion while design processing leaving the window of opportunity open to allow accidental discoveries and stimulation of creativity. Choice-architecture in most design strategies often leads to linear processing and results thereof, in RSFF we allow and afford random processing making numerous iterations incorporating and entailing a World of Ideas.','RSFF Education','','publish','open','open','','rsff-education','','','2010-06-24 14:34:33','2010-06-24 12:34:33','',0,'http://www.rawshaping.com/?p=413',0,'post','',0),
(425,7,'2010-07-06 16:40:11','2010-07-06 14:40:11','Here you can find more information on RSFF [rawshaping formfinding] assignments and student work second year Bachelor industrial design engineering education at the University of Twente in the Netherlands. The RSFF course is loosely structured on intuitive design, collaborative interaction, hybridization of design tools and choice-architecture of which all components are intwined and afford the potential ramifications of our choices and interventions in design ideation and conceptualization. Furthermore the RSFF course incorporates and focuses on theories, mediation, techniques, technical philosophy, and practices of hybrid design processing. RSFF is not constrained by the traditional boundaries of design, engineering and planning. The emphasis of RSFF is on multi-disciplinary collaborative interaction and the role ambiguity, chaos and unpredictability play in designing and design processing during ideation and abstract conceptualization.\n\nStudent contributions by: Liesbeth Stam, Ani Hovhannisjan, Leon Spikker, Wessel de Vries, José Boekema, Liza Boon, Jorn van Manen, Marleen Offringa, Simon Hollander, Sabine Mooij, Jeanine van der Hoek, Mike Broekman, Gilbert van Veldhuizen, Charlot Boelens, Titia Lelie, ...\n\n<strong>Assignment RSFF I</strong> shown here is based on intuitive two-handed tangible interaction with physical tools and materials leading to thinking-on-your-feet, knowing-in-action and reflection-on-action. The rigour versus relevance theorem bringing about the fuzzy-logic as a loosely fittted organizational technique for developing intelligent, flexible and adaptive shapes, objects and forms. Gestural and manipulation activity are manifestations of design intent evoking emerging possibilities of new abstractions and creative solutions to support creativity and ideation. In this assignment the real and the virtual are merged by shifting from traditional analogue physical representations to digital virtual artifacts. This co-localization supported by real-world models (role model) from physical manipulation and 3d-scanning of these free-forms stimulate the hybridization of the real and the virtual realms. Underlying aspect of this assignment is the cognitive charge ignited through skill, intuition and sensory stimulation.\n\n<img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF01-4a.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF01-5.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF01-6.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF01-7.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF01-8.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0171751_Hovhannisjan_Ani_RSFF01-1.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0171751_Hovhannisjan_Ani_RSFF01-2.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0171751_Hovhannisjan_Ani_RSFF01-3.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0171751_Hovhannisjan_Ani_RSFF01-2.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0171751_Hovhannisjan_Ani_RSFF01-3.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0171751_Hovhannisjan_Ani_RSFF01-4.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0174742_Spikker_Leon_rsff01%20-%20Copy-1.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0174742_Spikker_Leon_rsff01%20-%20Copy-2.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0185876_de_Vries_Wessel_RSFF01.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0191701_Boekema_Jos__RSSF01-1.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0191701_Boekema_Jos__RSSF01-2.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0191701_Boekema_Jos__RSSF01-3.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0191701_Boekema_Jos__RSSF01-4.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF01-2.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF01-3.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF01-4.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF01-5.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF01-6.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF01-7.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF01-8.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF01-9.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0201685_Manen_van_Jorn_RSFF01-2.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0201685_Manen_van_Jorn_RSFF01-3.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0201685_Manen_van_Jorn_RSFF01-4.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0201685_Manen_van_Jorn_RSFF01-5.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0201685_Manen_van_Jorn_RSFF01-6.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0215856_OffringaOpdracht_I-2.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0215856_OffringaOpdracht_I-3.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0215856_OffringaOpdracht_I-4.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0215856_OffringaOpdracht_I-5.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0215856_OffringaOpdracht_I-6.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0215856_OffringaOpdracht_I-7.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__I_s0215856_OffringaOpdracht_I-8.jpg\" /> [vimeo 15628496] [vimeo 15628653]\n\n<strong>Assignment RSFF II</strong> deals with lightweight design, mobility and spheres within nomadic cultures and organizational ephemeral structures. The emphasis is on sketching, ideation and three dimensional modeling of spatial solutions to create insight and understanding in spatial relationships, scalability and proportions. Unleashing the power of imagination by direct two-handed manipulation of tangible materials while stimulating observation, mediation and conceptualization. Design as an extension of Nature, the love of Nature and mimicking the serendipitous qualities of Nature encompass this assignment, supporting the need to embed and fit design in life as part of Nature. Loosely based on Sloterdijk\'s philosophy on Spheres about spaces of coexistence and the exploration of spheres in support of design thinking, communication and understanding of human behavior, mediation and manifestations of being. The nomadic aspects, globalization, lightweightness and creation of living spaces (spheres) are important aspects of this rawshaping design assignment.\n\n<img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF02-2.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF02-3.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF02-4.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF02-5.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF02-6.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF02-7.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF02-8.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0093025_Stam_Liesbeth_RSFF02-9.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0165425_Hollander_Simon_RSFF02.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0171751_Hovhannisjan_Ani_RSFF02-2.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0171751_Hovhannisjan_Ani_RSFF02-3.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0171751_Hovhannisjan_Ani_RSFF02-4.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF__II_s0171751_Hovhannisjan_Ani_RSFF02-5.jpg\" /> [vimeo 15628709] [vimeo 15630753]\n\n<strong>Assignment RSFF III</strong> is based on the double pendulum which undergoes and shows chaotic motion under initial conditions until it collapses. To track and visualize the chaotic motions LED lights are added to the limbs. The design and construction of the double pendulums are based on cheap and off-the-shelves components and materials to stimulate design students to make physical models and prototypes of their ideas and fuzzy notions. A variety of contraptions have been executed and fabricated on-the-fly, where loosely-fitted components become simple physical systems which can exhibit chaotic behavior. The results are shown in the images and videos in a wide variety of double pendulum visualizations.\n\n<img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0165425_Hollander_Simon_RSFF03.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0171751_Hovhannisian_Ani_RSFF03-2a.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0171751_Hovhannisian_Ani_RSFF03-3b.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0171751_Hovhannisian_Ani_RSFF03-4.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF_03-1.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF_03-10.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF_03-11.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF_03-12.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF_03-13.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF_03-3.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF_03-4.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF_03-5.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0200212_Boon_Liza_RSFF_03-6.jpg\" /> <img src=\"_10 http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/10/RSFF_III_s0200212