(706,7,'2011-03-18 22:03:20','2011-03-18 20:03:20','During the VRIC 2011 conference at Laval Virtual, Robert E. Wendrich will present a paper on \'Distributed Cognition, Mimic, Representation and Decision Making\'. Based on experimentation findings and results in conjunction with a real-world case-study on Hybrid Interaction Environments in Support of Collaborative Design Processes.\n\nFor the program: <a href=\"http://www.laval-virtual.org/doc/VRIC/VRICprogram2011.pdf\">http://www.laval-virtual.org/doc/VRIC/VRICprogram2011.pdf</a>\n\nor here: [pdf VRICprogram2011.pdf]\n\nFor more information: <a href=\"http://www.laval-virtual.org\">http://www.laval-virtual.org</a>','VRIC 2011 ','','publish','open','open','','vric-2011','','','2011-03-18 22:03:20','2011-03-18 20:03:20','',0,'http://www.rawshaping.com/?p=706',0,'post','',0),
(709,7,'2011-03-18 22:06:38','2011-03-18 20:06:38','LFDS is a workbench approach for design and engineering interaction to stimulate intuition, creativity and imagination of the ideation and conceptualization process. An important aspect of the workbench is the standing up posture of the user (-s) during interaction which enhances the experience, intuits knowledge of the user-interface and enhances the interaction with the tool functionality. The LFDS hybrid design tool is based on a mixed-reality that allows physical two-handed manipulation with real-world materials and tools, simultaneously assisted by a virtual assistant. Special physical user-interfaces are present to support the user in the interaction, creation and decision-making process. The iterations emerging from the sequential interaction are captured real-time by a HD video camera. The user is in control of capturing the iterative instances by pushing a red capture-button or foot pedal. The virtual visualization of the instances affords the user to select, sort, stack, structure and/or organize the variety and diversity in serendipitous content. A special user interface allows for easy navigation on screen to support and assist in the decision making process. All the captured iterative instances in the virtual realm are time-stamps in the listing and can freely be synthesized to stimulate the choice-architecture. Once sorted and selected according to the need (-s) of the user (-s) the instances can be stacked, saved, exported or re-iterated. Furthermore, the instances can be labeled, rated and/or ranked real-time and stacks can be created fluidly.\r\n\r\nWe mimic, we reflect, we adapt ourselves continuously to our environment. Our senses are attentive, dose off or are triggered by impulses and cues from the world around us. We react and act according to our understanding and in some cases we move forward on a hunch. We adapt and comply willingly to change, and more often we do not accept change fullheartedly by rejecting the requested adaptation. Designers are known to change their minds continuously and in the spur of the moment being ambiguous in their choices and directions. During ideation and fabrication of full concepts the need for speed and fast iterations is a prerequisite to stimulate the creation process. Representations of ideas by creating abstract visual illustrations of mental models and through the devise of tangible working prototypes ideas are externalized and communicate spatial relationships within contexts. Traditional analogue design tools still have a place in design representation and interaction, next to the digital design tools. Face-to-face interaction between designers or multiple players (collaborative) play a strong role during ideation and working with sketchy information. To convey ideas and provoke thoughts by others we look at each other. This interaction between people creates a visual, nudging and tacit understanding to evoke a mental picture of the given objective or design task.\r\n\r\nAccording to Don Norman we manage well in the natural world, interpreting the signs and signals of the environment and its inhabitants. Our perceptual system conveys a rich sense of space, created from the seamless combination of sights, and sounds, smells and feelings that surround us. Our proprioceptive system conveys information from the semicircular canals of the inner ear and our muscles, tendons, and joints to give us a sense of body location and orientation. We identify events and objects rapidly, often from minimal cues – a brief glimpse or sound, for instance. But more importantly natural signals inform without annoyance, providing a natural, nonintrusive, nonirritating, continuous awareness of the events around us. Based on our research into distributed cognition and the sensory somatic aspects of interaction and behavior combined with analogue and digital representation modes of communication we developed and build the Loosely Fitted Design Synthesizer [LFDS].\r\n\r\n<img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/workbench%20rgb.jpg\" />\r\n\r\n[vimeo 20834839]','Loosely Fitted Design Synthesizer [LFDS]','','publish','open','open','','loosely-fitted-design-synthesizer-lfds','','','2013-03-28 12:41:15','2013-03-28 12:41:15','',0,'http://www.rawshaping.com/?p=709',0,'post','',0),
