(1425,7,'2013-03-28 12:42:03','2013-03-28 12:42:03','On Tuesday May 24th, 2011 the Raw Shaping Society launched their hybrid design tool LFDS [Loosely Fitted Design Synthesizer] in Design Education context. Over ninety (90) Bachelor students in Industrial Design at the University of Twente were immersed in design ideation and creative exploration in conjunction with the hybrid tools. The students were asked to group randomly in Design Pairs. The Design Pairs were given an assignment to design a vehicle or automotive object. The paired collaborative session lasted for five (5) minutes, to make speedy iterations with tangible materials. We offered two complete horizontal LFDS workbenches and systems for the design sessions. Each LFDS Workbench had one moderator to assist in case of dire need. Furthermore the students were given a set of two dimensional \'wheels\' to trigger their initial ideas. Results of the student sessions will be posted at later date.\n\nFor some videos:\n\n[vimeo 24266658] [vimeo 24275139] [vimeo 24279573]\n\nFor pictures:\n\n<img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu01.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu02.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu04.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu05.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu06.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu08.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu09.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu13.jpg\" />','RSFF Launches LFDS in Design Education 2011','','inherit','open','open','','759-autosave','','','2013-03-28 12:42:03','2013-03-28 12:42:03','',759,'http://www.rawshaping.com/?p=1425',0,'revision','',0),
(1426,7,'2013-03-28 12:43:35','2013-03-28 12:43:35','LFDS is a workbench approach for design and engineering interaction to stimulate intuition, creativity and imagination of the ideation and conceptualization process. An important aspect of the workbench is the standing up posture of the user (-s) during interaction which enhances the experience, intuits knowledge of the user-interface and enhances the interaction with the tool functionality. The LFDS hybrid design tool is based on a mixed-reality that allows physical two-handed manipulation with real-world materials and tools, simultaneously assisted by a virtual assistant. Special physical user-interfaces are present to support the user in the interaction, creation and decision-making process. The iterations emerging from the sequential interaction are captured real-time by a HD video camera. The user is in control of capturing the iterative instances by pushing a red capture-button or foot pedal. The virtual visualization of the instances affords the user to select, sort, stack, structure and/or organize the variety and diversity in serendipitous content. A special user interface allows for easy navigation on screen to support and assist in the decision making process. All the captured iterative instances in the virtual realm are time-stamps in the listing and can freely be synthesized to stimulate the choice-architecture. Once sorted and selected according to the need (-s) of the user (-s) the instances can be stacked, saved, exported or re-iterated. Furthermore, the instances can be labeled, rated and/or ranked real-time and stacks can be created fluidly.\n\nWe mimic, we reflect, we adapt ourselves continuously to our environment. Our senses are attentive, dose off or are triggered by impulses and cues from the world around us. We react and act according to our understanding and in some cases we move forward on a hunch. We adapt and comply willingly to change, and more often we do not accept change fullheartedly by rejecting the requested adaptation. Designers are known to change their minds continuously and in the spur of the moment being ambiguous in their choices and directions. During ideation and fabrication of full concepts the need for speed and fast iterations is a prerequisite to stimulate the creation process. Representations of ideas by creating abstract visual illustrations of mental models and through the devise of tangible working prototypes ideas are externalized and communicate spatial relationships within contexts. Traditional analogue design tools still have a place in design representation and interaction, next to the digital design tools. Face-to-face interaction between designers or multiple players (collaborative) play a strong role during ideation and working with sketchy information. To convey ideas and provoke thoughts by others we look at each other. This interaction between people creates a visual, nudging and tacit understanding to evoke a mental picture of the given objective or design task.\n\nAccording to Don Norman we manage well in the natural world, interpreting the signs and signals of the environment and its inhabitants. Our perceptual system conveys a rich sense of space, created from the seamless combination of sights, and sounds, smells and feelings that surround us. Our proprioceptive system conveys information from the semicircular canals of the inner ear and our muscles, tendons, and joints to give us a sense of body location and orientation. We identify events and objects rapidly, often from minimal cues – a brief glimpse or sound, for instance. But more importantly natural signals inform without annoyance, providing a natural, nonintrusive, nonirritating, continuous awareness of the events around us. Based on our research into distributed cognition and the sensory somatic aspects of interaction and behavior combined with analogue and digital representation modes of communication we developed and build the Loosely Fitted Design Synthesizer [LFDS].\n\n<img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/workbench%20rgb.jpg\" />\n\n[vimeo 20834839]','Loosely Fitted Design Synthesizer [LFDS]','','inherit','open','open','','709-autosave','','','2013-03-28 12:43:35','2013-03-28 12:43:35','',709,'http://www.rawshaping.com/?p=1426',0,'revision','',0),
(1427,7,'2011-05-26 14:47:33','2011-05-26 12:47:33','On Tuesday May 24th, 2011 the Raw Shaping Society launched their hybrid design tool LFDS [Loosely Fitted Design Synthesizer] in Design Education context. Over ninety (90) Bachelor students in Industrial Design at the University of Twente were immersed in design ideation and creative exploration in conjunction with the hybrid tools. The students were asked to group randomly in Design Pairs. The Design Pairs were given an assignment to design a vehicle or automotive object. The paired collaborative session lasted for five (5) minutes, to make speedy iterations with tangible materials. We offered two complete horizontal LFDS workbenches and systems for the design sessions. Each LFDS Workbench had one moderator to assist in case of dire need. Furthermore the students were given a set of two dimensional \'wheels\' to trigger their initial ideas. Results of the student sessions will be posted at later date.\n\nFor some videos:\n\n[vimeo 24266658] [vimeo 24275139] [vimeo 24279573]\n\nFor pictures:\n\n<img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu01.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu02.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu04.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu05.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu06.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu08.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu09.jpg\" /> <img src=\" http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/LFDS%20Edu13.jpg\" />','RSFF Launches LFDS in Design Education 2011','','inherit','open','open','','759-revision','','','2011-05-26 14:47:33','2011-05-26 12:47:33','',759,'http://www.rawshaping.com/?p=1427',0,'revision','',0),
(1428,7,'2013-03-28 12:44:51','2013-03-28 12:44:51','[I\'ve read the news today...oh boy...no news from this front.]\n\nMay 2011\n\nWe launched the LFDS hybrid design tool in Design Education. We immersed over ninety (90)  students in design interaction in conjunction with the LFDS. They were grouped in pairs to accomplish a specific design task. Apart from the keeness, curiosity and enjoyment the students made hundreds of speedy iterations and instances. We will post some of the results at later date this site.\n\nMay 2011\n\nRobert will present his paper about Novel Approach in Custom Value Engineering during the WINVR2011 Conference in Milan, Italy end of June. We\'ll keep you notified.\n\nApril 2011\n\nLaval Virtual 2011 was superb, we demoed the LFDS for three days during the Pro-Exhibition resulting in great response and enthusiasm of the visitors. Robert presented his paper during the  VRIC2011 about Cognition, Intuition and Interaction Design. All in all great experience, great time and harmonious work.\n\nFebruary 2011\n\nOur contribution to VRIC2011, Virtual Laval in France, has been accepted! We will keep you posted.\n\nJanuary 2011\n\nOur Video contribution on LFDS  to the IEEE VR2011 Conference in Singapore has been accepted!  Instead of writing another paper on the Hybrid Design Tool we decided to present a video on our [re]search endeavors and experimentations. Good start of the new year...! Nice going!\n\nDecember 2010\n\nRSFF is working\n\nNovember 5th, 2010\n\nWe did a Value Engineering session at ProRail in Utrecht with our LFDS Design Tool, impressive and exciting event with a variety in stakeholders working on a real life Project Alkmaar. This next generation of Railway stations 2015  will incorporate new visions on traffic flows of  passengers, commercial areas and infra-structural traffic systems.\n\nFor more information see the post on the home page.\n\nSeptember 27th - October 1st, 2010\n\nDuring the JVRC 2010 (Joint Virtual Reality Conference) in Stuttgart, Robert E. Wendrich will  be presenting and demonstrating a prototype of the LFDS [Loosely Fitted Design Synthesizer]. He will also present first results of working with the LFDS in a real world case-based scenario for ProRail [Dutch National Railway] in the Netherlands.\n\nFollow this link for more information: <a href=\"http://www.jvrc2010.org/\">http://www.jvrc2010.org/</a>\n\nMay 20th, 2010\n\nWell it is a fact, RSFF has been published in a International CAD Journal! Computer-Aided Design and Applications (ISSN 1686-4360) is an independent, international peer-reviewed technical journal dedicated to the applications of computer-aided design and manufacturing. This special issue is titled CAD in the Arts and RSFF is part of it!\n\n[pdf CADandA_7_4_505-531.pdf]\n\nMay 4th, 2010\n\nRobert E. Wendrich will be presenting \'RSFF: Exploring Intuitive Design through Tangible Real &amp; Virtual Real\'  during the Conference of Bridges: Mathematical Connections in Art, Music and Science. The conference will take place in Pécs, Hungary, during July 24 - 29, 2010.\n\n<a href=\"http://bridgesmathart.org/bridges-2010/\">http://bridgesmathart.org/bridges-2010/</a>\n\nApril 13th, 2010\n\nRobert E. Wendrich will be Keynote at the ASME 2010 World Conference on Innovative Virtual Reality (WINVR2010) in Ames, Iowa, USA on May 12-14th to speak about RSFF: Hybrid Design Tool.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.asmeconferences.org/WINVR2010/\">http://www.asmeconferences.org/WINVR2010/</a>\n\nApril 9th, 2010\n\nRobert E. Wendrich will be presenting during the EuroVR conference in Paris  on May 6 - 7th speaking on RSFF: Hybrid Design Tool and [re]search challenges in VR/AR technologies for design activities.\n\n<a href=\"http://eurovr-eve-2010.limsi.fr\">http://eurovr-eve-2010.limsi.fr</a>\n\nApril 8th, 2010\n\nRSFF WINNER of the VIRTUAL LAVAL AWARD 2010\n\nRSFF: Hybrid Design Tool came out as the winner of the category Industrial Design and Simulation!\n\nBubbles...','RSFF News','','inherit','open','open','','291-autosave','','','2013-03-28 12:44:51','2013-03-28 12:44:51','',291,'http://www.rawshaping.com/?p=1428',0,'revision','',0),
