(1569,7,'2014-03-24 11:15:14','2014-03-24 11:15:14','The <strong>ASME 2014 International Design and Engineering Technical Conferences &amp; Computers and Information in Engineering Conference (IDETC/CIE 2014)</strong> will take place during <strong>August 17-20, 2014</strong> in Buffalo, NY, USA.\r\n\r\nVES: Game Eco-Systems in Engineering:\r\n\r\nThe following list details the breakdown of themes that would include the above mentioned topics. The Track envisages as a starting compendium for serious gaming concepts that make up a game ecosystem for engineering. Knowledge discovery in SG-VES: a human-centered approach - Knowledge acquisition by user experience - Serious games and emotional interaction in learning and transfer of knowledge - Study on pervasive systems and gameplay experiences - Mapping of learning goals to (serious) game mechanics Software architecture and design - Game and game engine architecture - Game design in theory and practice Feedback and game/learning mechanics for engineering physics (includes human-computer interaction, game engines, analytics and assessment frameworks, game authoring, asset creation and management, etc.) - Human Interface Devices SG-VES Applications - Applied and research platforms for engineering physics - Big Data/ Data Exploration in High Value Manufacturing/Engineering Sectors, Space Applications and the Physical Sciences, Creative Industries - Product design and manufacturing: modeling, authoring, control and concurrent workspaces (includes haptic-VR techniques, pervasive techniques and social networks, life cycle management, etc.) - Transportation engineering: modeling (includes driving simulation and traffic modeling) - Medical and clinical: Surgical training, sensorimotor rehabilitation, etc. - Robotics: Simulation and Emulation; Design; Evaluation; Deployment; Control Cyber-physical systems - Mechanistic / Humanistic / Biomimetic approaches - Body Area Networks for VES (live role play problem solving; run-time au