(1652,7,'2014-12-09 16:14:31','2014-12-09 16:14:31','<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Rawshaping Technology will take part during the Designers Day Event organized by WWF and Plastic Soup Lab on Tuesday December 16th, 2014, where they will collaboratively ideate, create and tinker concept(-s) for the local waters of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. They will bring their hybrid design tools to assist them in their creative design processing.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/WWF.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1657\" alt=\"WWF\" src=\"http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/WWF.png\" width=\"593\" height=\"670\" /></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">For more information:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://plasticsoupfoundation.org\">http://plasticsoupfoundation.org</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://wwf.panda.org/\">http://wwf.panda.org/</a></p>\r\nPlastic pollution\r\nThere are several levels to address the plastic problem: design, production, use, waste collection &amp; treatment, clean-up and restoration. Innovations such as the Ocean Cleanup from Boyan Slat are aimed at cleaning up the plastics that are already trapped in currents of the gyres. The growth of plastic waste in the ocean can be reduced. The vast majority of this pollution comes from the land; plastic waste is discharged by industry and in cities and finds its way out to the sea through rivers, canals and ports. Additionally, ships, the fishing industry and the offshore industry are important plastic polluters.\r\n\r\nRio de Janeiro\r\nSolid waste in the local waters of Rio de Janeiro is omnipresent and before the start of the Rio 2016 Olympic and Paralympic games a cleaner (surface) water system is of utmost importance for the local responsible authorities. WWF NL/WWF Brazil and the Plastic Soup Foundation are researching the feasibility of the development of a consumer product (possibly linked to the Olympic Games) from plastic marine litter coming from slums and ending up in the Guanabara Bay in Rio de Janeiro, while benefiting the local community (both health conditions and resources).\r\n\r\nDesigners Day\r\nIn the morning there are several presentation on the quality of the plastics that can be used, the current situation in Rio de Janeiro, the production method and the life cycle analysis. After lunch it’s time to work on the concepts. There is a chance that your design will be selected to get presented to potential investors in Rio de Janeiro in March 2015. We can’t promise anything, but this might mean that a few of you will meet your designer colleagues from Brazil!','RST@Designers Day: Design & Recycling','','publish','open','closed','','rstdesigners-day-design-recycling','','','2014-12-09 16:31:25','2014-12-09 16:31:25','',0,'http://www.rawshaping.com/?p=1652',0,'post','',0),
