(1891,7,'2017-04-27 12:47:08','2017-04-27 12:47:08','<img src=\"http://www.asmeconferences.org/IDETC2017/images/IDETC2017Header.gif\" align=\"absbottom\" border=\"0\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>Virtual Environments and Systems (VES)</strong>\r\n\r\nThe range of functions and features in CAD products for mechanical engineering and related domains are seemingly ever expanding. This complicates the product development process due to an escalating number of components, complexity between the interactions among these components as well as by a growing number of involved team members and stakeholders. Virtual reality environments, immersive VR, and systems offer an opportunity to cope with these challenges. The essence of immersive virtual reality is the illusion of going inside the computer-generated world as if it is a place you are visiting. The essence of augmented virtual reality is to integrate digital images into the real world. Systems for virtual environments encompass all hardware (interaction devices, system architectures, projection systems) and software (rendering methods, data management), which is required to deploy this type of virtual environments. For example, coupling gaming with VR shows promise for ideation innovation. Smart phone display technology has caught on and quickly changed the world using display screens for the VR goggles (e.g. play and games). The symposium of virtual environments and systems (VES) is a platform to introduce, demonstrate, and discuss the latest advances in Virtual Reality environment, applications and systems for mechanical engineering and related domains.\r\n\r\n<strong>VES PANEL On: Advancement in Digital Technology Systems, Usage of Virtual Reality and Tools for Engineering</strong>\r\n\r\nAs the market and/or industrial interest in virtual environments increase, new technologies and techniques are proposed. In recent years we have observed a trend on the use of low-cost devices, so metimes taken from the gaming industry in industrial applications. Furthermore, companies are investing billions into making immersive virtual worlds and augmented reality widely available to mainstream public in mass quantities (i.e., especially for “gamer” consumers but also a wide range of other applications). We have also seen a trend in customization. Nowadays, thanks to the availability of 3-D printing technologies as well as open-source electronic prototyping platform, custom interfaces can be easily designed. We have observed a shift of interest from Virtual Environment to Mixed ones, sometimes called Augmented, sometimes named \"Blended\". Furthermore as the number of applications increases, new challenges are presented to the scientific community. This purpose of this VES panel is to encourage discussion and exchange of views about current and new trends for Virtual and Immersive/Blended Systems and the transference of knowledge over multiple domains.\r\n\r\n<strong>VES SYMPOSIUMS:</strong>\r\n<table border=\"0\" width=\"100%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>CIE-21 Virtual Environments and Systems (VES)</strong> <em> (Symposium)</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">Symposium Organizer: Robert E. Wendrich, <em>IDE at University of Twente</em>\r\nLocation: Enschede , Netherlands\r\nEmail: <a href=\"mailto:info@rawshaping.com\">info@rawshaping.com</a>Symposium Co-Organizer: Pramita Mitra, <em>Ford Motor Company</em>\r\nLocation: Bloomfield Township , MI , United States\r\nEmail: <a href=\"mailto:pmitra3@ford.com\">pmitra3@ford.com</a>\r\n\r\nSymposium Co-Organizer: Theo Lim, <em>Heriot-watt Univ</em>\r\nLocation: Edinburgh , Scotland\r\nEmail: <a href=\"mailto:t.lim@hw.ac.uk\">t.lim@hw.ac.uk</a>\r\n<table border=\"0\" width=\"100%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>CIE-22 VES: Technology and Applications (TA)</strong> <em> (Symposium)</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">Symposium Organizer: Robert E. We