(1898,7,'2017-04-27 13:13:30','2017-04-27 13:13:30','<img class=\"wp-image-1904 size-full aligncenter\" src=\"http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/stranded.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"242\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">© Robert Wendrich</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-1905\" src=\"http://www.rawshaping.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/bill-reid-haida-grizzly-serigraph-3200-vancouver_8161994-350x349.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">© Bill Read - \'Grizzly\'</p>\r\n<strong>Rawshaping Technology @ ICED 2017 will present a paper:</strong>\r\n\r\n<em> Blow Bits: Creative Playgrounds, Gamification and Virtuosity with Hybrid Design Tools and Environments (HDTE)</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Another paper was unfortunately (surprisingly) not accepted, however very much fitting to the topic:</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Discover Raw Serendipity: Stimulate potential skills and enhance creativity in people</em>\r\n\r\n<em>The argument on visual and meta-cognitive stimuli constructed from multiple experiences and multiple modalities in helping ideation and concept generation is well received. The paper attempts to present a new approach to stimulating creativity based on the use specific types of tools. Your area of research, and your aspirations around the reversed IEK framework is valuable and needed.</em>\r\n\r\nIn keeping with the critical nature of natural and human resources to Canada, and especially to the province of BC, the overarching theme of ICED17 is “<strong>Resource-Sensitive Design</strong>”.\r\nWe will have special events and activities to showcase this theme as it is interwoven throughout the workshops and sessions that will span the traditional ICED topics.\r\n\r\n<strong>“Resource-Sensitive Design”. </strong>This general theme encompasses three main areas. The first is “<em>Design to advance resource-limited societies</em>”, or how to design products that succeed given limited infrastructure, uncertain supply chains and cultural factors that impact product introduction. Second, <em>Design to protect critical resources</em>: especially in British Columbia, how do limits on critical natural resources such as oil, gas, water, and forestry define how products are designed and fabricated?  And third, <em>Design to embrace resource limitations</em>, or, how can all of us learn to design with a minimalistic approach: elegant, functional design through simplicity.','RST@ICED2017 - Vancouver, BC, Canada','','publish','open','closed','','rsticed2017-vancouver-bc-canada','','','2017-04-27 13:32:00','2017-04-27 13:32:00','',0,'http://www.rawshaping.com/?p=1898',0,'post','',0),
